<font color="#FF0000">INFORMATION</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 25 23:03:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all vet,<br>
Through my psychology experience in college and my involvement in Veterans causes, I have come across in my travels a 13-point combat scale used by psycholgists to determine the combat intensity a vet was exposed to.  A determination of the degree of combat a vet has seen makes the psycholgist aware of the degree of probability that a patient may suffer from.  It also helps the psychologist decide how he will deal with a veteran.  The scale/test was prepared by Dr Mark Gallop, Dr. Robert Laufer and Dr. Thomas Yeager.  I hear even the VA uses it.  Test yourself and find out where a psychologist would rate our combat intensity exposure (key to PTSD).<br><br>
The 13 point combat scale<br><br>
Simply answer YES or NO to each question.  Each question has <br>
a point value.  Only add up the points to questions you answered yes to.<br><br>
questions<br>
1.  Did you serve in a artillery unit that fired on an emeny?     Point value=1<br>
2.  Did you fly over Vietnam in an aircraft (helicopter or other)?  Point value=1<br>
3.  Were you ever stationed at a foward observation post?<br>
Point value=1<br>
4.  Did you ever receive incoming fire?  Point value=1<br>
5.  Did you ever encounter mines or boobytraps? <br>
 Point value=1<br>
6.  Did you ever receive sniper or sapper fire?<br>
point value=1<br>
7.  Was your unit or patrol ambushed?  Point value=2<br>
8.  Did you ever engage the VC/NVA in firefight? <br>
point value=2<br>
9.  Did you see Americans killed or saw Vietnamese killed?<br>
point value=2<br>
10.  Were you wounded? Point value=2<br><br>
Now add up the point values for the questions you answered YES to only.  <br><br>
Results<br>
 An answer of no on all questions (0 points) results in a <br>
&quot;noncombat&quot; classification.<br>
A score of 1 through 6 is rated as &quot;low combat&quot; veteran.<br>
A score of 7 through 14 is rated as a &quot;high combat&quot; veteran.<br><br>
A high score doesn't necessarily mean one will suffer from PTSD, nor does a low score rule it out.  In general the more combat exposure, the higher the probability of PTSD and the greater seberity of the disorder.<br><br>
Some studies even show that non combat vets may have more guilty feelings than combat ones, since they feel they &quot;didn't do their part&quot;.  I can't attest to the accuracy of this particular statement because I have not seen all the particulars of the studies involved<br><br>
I hope the 13 point scale helps some vets out.  Good luck and God bless to you all.  In the days of the American Revolutionary War, the new US Army lit barn fires to help lost soldiers find their way back to their lines.  Some of us will always keep the barn fires lit so you guys can find your way back home.
<p><code>-- Peace!!  (Joseph DeLeva) </code><p>


